	(2490,548,'_trainers','field_5b11084b0b702'),
	(2491,548,'overview','Dear Julian,\r\n\r\nIt was good to meet you and thank you for your time and commitment during the recent media training session. We hope that you found the insight into the journalists agenda useful, and that you will be able to use some of the lessons learned in future engagements.\r\n\r\nIn this note, we capture the main feedback points from the session, where you performed well, and where there are areas to work on.\r\n\r\nWe recommend that you look back at your performances in the private portal we provide for you. Please click through the thumbnail on the portal.\r\n\r\n<strong><em>Introduction </em></strong>\r\n\r\nIn the session, we focused on the broadcast media and simulated a radio from the perspective of the business slot on BBC Radio 4s Today programme and two TV interviews; a face-to-face studio interview with Ian King Live on Sky News and a down-the-line interview with ITV news. We believe this gives our clients relevant insight and experience of the different demands of each format so that you can prepare appropriately.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;'),
	(2492,548,'_overview','field_5b1023299fc62'),
	(2493,548,'went_well','<ul>\r\n 	<li>You convey warmth and expertise and have an apparent depth of knowledge that was delivered in an authoritative but down-to-earth manner. You did well to get in your good morning greeting in the Today interview and always appeared to be pleased to be representing BCL Solicitors. We discussed the importance of this; people are more likely to listen to you and believe what you say if you appear to be upbeat and positive in saying it.</li>\r\n 	<li>You are particularly skilful in re-framing the context and dynamic of the interview by resisting a repetition of the negative language of the question and using your own positive vocabulary instead. The disaster of losing Europol to a no-deal Brexit was converted to serious risk and we particularly liked the translation of Ian Kings mish-mash of legislation to your patchwork.</li>\r\n 	<li>You were right to avoid the use of acronyms and industry jargon by spelling out The Data Protection Act and explaining the relevance of GDPR to our personal data.</li>\r\n 	<li>You absorbed all the advice, adjusting your pace of delivery and using the helicopter to smoothly re-set the context of the ITV down-the-line interview and speak about the effects of a disorderly Brexit. This was impressive.\r\n\r\n<strong>Myddleton</strong>: Julian, you did well to explain that crimes do not have national boundaries and that our safety is paramount.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li>You looked comfortable in this tricky style of interview, putting your energy into gesture, and delivering with strong and constant eye-line to the lens. You looked engaged and in control and did particularly well to hold your eye line to the camera, rather than rushing off at the end. This was great to see.</li>\r\n</ul>'),
	(2494,548,'_went_well','field_5b21350c1cb97'),
	(2495,548,'more_work','<ul>\r\n 	<li>Do not let your manners get in the way of delivering your intent. We discussed the use of the helicopter to avoid a discussion about Trump, the threat of Russia and a no-deal Brexit before focusing on your prepared points.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li>Although you did well not to repeat the headline-grabbing language of the question of the disaster of crashing out of Europe, it is important to say: you did not say that, when wrongly accused than you just said it would be a disaster.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li>Similarly, having skilfully pushed away from the TalkTalk question, do not feel the need to go back to it and cause further discussion on a matter outside of your remit. Be careful about introducing a discussion about loopholes, which as we discussed, could risk positioning BCL Solicitors in a negative light.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li>When interrupted, it is important to resist matching the pace of the presenter and to insist on finishing your point. Slow the pace and re-define the dynamic, putting you back in the driving seat.</li>\r\n 	<li>Be aware of your listening position; your mouth movements can betray your discomfort. We also advised that you use your hands more than the rest of your body during interviews, to avoid the distracting effect of the movements that we saw in the Sky News interview.</li>\r\n</ul>'),
	(2496,548,'_more_work','field_5b23849124c44'),
	(2497,548,'conclusions','At the beginning of the session, we asked you about your personal brand and how you wanted to come across, you said:\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li><strong><em>Knowledgeable (as if I know what I am talking about) </em></strong> Yes, you achieved this from the start, even if Brexit was not the matter you had intended to discuss, what you said was clearly from an expert perspective.</li>\r\n 	<li><strong><em>Competent and calming </em></strong> Yes, notably in the down-the-line interview, you were serene, delivering with confidence in this tricky style of interview.</li>\r\n 	<li><strong><em>Reassuring - </em></strong>Yes, you were adept in taking the helicopter view and concerning yourself with the effects of Brexit on your clients, rather an indulging in a debate about a no-deal disaster.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nThe key point is to build-in a preparation process in partnership with Myddleton ahead of all media engagements that allows you to identify your key messages and develop memorable proof points to support them. You have the style and gravitas to be an excellent media asset for BCL Solicitors.\r\n\r\nIf there is anything more Bladonmore can help with, please do not hesitate to get in contact with us through Paul, Deborah or Paula.\r\n\r\nKind regards,\r\nMatt Guarente and Susan Bookbinder\r\n\r\n&nbsp;'),
