	(4857,629,'_trainers','field_5b11084b0b702'),
	(4858,629,'overview','It was good to meet you last week. Thank you for your time and effort during the media training session.\r\n\r\nWe hope you found the insight into the journalists agenda useful, and that you will be able to use some of the lessons learned in future engagements.\r\n\r\nIn this note, we capture the main feedback points from the session, where you performed well, and where there are areas to work on.\r\n\r\n<strong><em>Introduction</em></strong>\r\n\r\nIn the session, we focused on the broadcast media and simulated a radio interview on BBC Radio Five Live and two TV interviews: a face-to-face studio interview with Kay Burley on Sky News and a clip for a package with ITV News at Ten. We believe this gives you relevant insight and experience of the different demands of each format so that you can prepare appropriately.'),
	(4859,629,'_overview','field_5b1023299fc62'),
	(4860,629,'went_well','<ul>\r\n 	<li>You dealt with difficult subject matter with dignity and empathy. For example, in the second interview on the death at Pret, you said the first priority was to find out exactly what happened  for the family, and to make sure that it would not happen again. This response, putting people first, showed humanity and authority, helping the audience to like you and trust you at the same time. Throughout all the interviews, you were calm, even when being asked tricky questions. This conveyed a dependable, competent and approachable style, which again will help you win confidence and trust from the audience.</li>\r\n 	<li>You did well to brand BCL Solicitors in every interview. This can come over as somewhat crass and cumbersome, but you were elegant and discreet about mentioning the name of the firm, particularly as you did so in relation to your focus on discovering the truth (as opposed to helping clients get away with crime).</li>\r\n 	<li>You backed up your assertions with clear evidence. For example, when asked if you would defend the Kensington and Chelsea Council you responded with a clear Certainly and went on to provide evidence of your track record in this area, citing the Lakanal fire. This was excellent and would certainly give confidence to anyone listening, including from the Kensington and Chelsea Council, that you are someone who could handle their case should they face charges.</li>\r\n 	<li>You did not repeat negative language. For example, you were right to resist repeating the negative language of a question that referenced the rat problem at one of your clients, Holland and Barrett. Instead, you selected the parts of the question that you wanted to respond to and in so doing skilfully moved the conversation away from rats back to Pret.</li>\r\n 	<li>You absorbed all our advice, delivering an excellent sound-bite in the ITV News interview, which could be used in isolation, without needing to include the reporters question. Ensuring that you repeat the part of the question with which you agree in this format helps in the editing process and increases your chances of being quoted.</li>\r\n</ul>'),
	(4861,629,'_went_well','field_5b21350c1cb97'),
	(4862,629,'more_work','<ul>\r\n 	<li>Be more definite. In the broadcast format, you do not have much time to make an impact. Remember that you are there as an expert witness  your years of experience lend you authority on this subject matter in the eyes and ears of your audience; dont be afraid to leverage it. Replace vague words and phrases like its an interesting comment for him to have made (in the first interview) with more definite, even critical observations, where appropriate; instead of talking about what you hope Pret is doing in response to a crisis, tell us what you would advise them to do. Myddleton will help you to establish how close to the line you as a firm are happy to go on different topics.</li>\r\n 	<li>Be aware of your body language. We discussed the importance of appearing to be pleased to be speaking on behalf of BCL Solicitors and engaged in the conversation. In the first interview you didnt look as engaged as you sounded. Even on radio, it is important for the two to be congruent as people  including the journalist  are more likely to listen to what you have to say and believe you, if you appear passionate and interested in the discussion. Of course, on certain topics it is not appropriate to smile, but a small thing like sitting up and leaning slightly forward  even using your hands  will help you to appear engaged and build rapport with the person asking the questions.</li>\r\n 	<li>Avoid potential pitfalls by focusing on what is rather than what is not. For example, when the interviewer mentioned Hillsborough as an example of how long it can take to bring charges and asked why these things take so long, it would have been better to go straight in with your point about the complexity of investigations. By saying Hillsborough was an outlier and devoting some time to explaining why (although you may be right), you risked getting drawn into an argument on that subject<strong>Myddleton: You did well to highlight that it was an inadequate investigation hindered by a cover up and that Corporate Manslaughter is very different from general crime.</strong></li>\r\n 	<li>Be careful of language in the context of the interview. Generally, you handled the very delicate subject matter well and with dignity. Just be careful of certain phrases like move on which, in the context of a death, might appear like you dont care and are only interested in the company getting past this.</li>\r\n 	<li>A few on-camera tips. Firstly, keep in mind that the camera saps energy so you must give more to achieve a given level of impact. Secondly, dont be afraid to use your hands  they are a useful outlet for nervous energy and freeing them up will help you to feel more relaxed. Thirdly, watch out for your eyeline. Unless you are filming down-the-line (where you are looking straight into the camera), look at the interviewer and dont glance at the camera as it is unsettling for the audience (who are not expecting you to make eye contact with them). If you need to look away, just look briefly down and then back up to the interviewer.</li>\r\n</ul>'),
	(4863,629,'_more_work','field_5b23849124c44'),
	(4864,629,'conclusions','At the beginning of the session, when we asked you about your personal brand and how you wanted to come across, you said:\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li><strong><em>Knowledgeable </em></strong> yes, you achieved this from the start.</li>\r\n 	<li><strong><em>Down to earth </em></strong> yes, notably in the Sky News interview when you spoke about the importance of finding out what happened for the family and to make sure it wouldnt happen again.</li>\r\n 	<li><strong><em>Friendly </em></strong> yes, you looked much happier to be speaking on behalf of BCL Solicitors in the second and third interviews.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nThe key point is to build-in a preparation process in partnership with Myddleton ahead of all media engagements that allows you to identify your key messages and develop memorable proof points so support them. You have the authority and approachability to be a powerful media asset for BCL Solicitors.\r\n\r\nKind regards,\r\n\r\nSusan Bookbinder and Shreena Patel'),
	(4865,629,'_conclusions','field_5b1023779fc64'),
