	(4910,634,'overview','It was good to meet you last week. Thank you for your time and effort during the media training session.\r\n\r\nWe hope you found the insight into the journalists agenda useful, and that you will be able to use some of the lessons learned in future engagements.\r\n\r\nIn this note, we capture the main feedback points from the session, where you performed well, and where there are areas to work on.\r\n\r\n<strong><em>Introduction </em></strong>\r\n\r\nIn the session, we focused on the broadcast media and simulated a radio from the perspective of the business slot on BBC Radio 4s Today programme and two TV interviews: a face-to-face studio interview with Ian King Live on Sky News and a down-the-line clip for a package with BBC News at Ten. We believe this gives you relevant insight and experience of the different demands of each format so that you can prepare appropriately.'),
	(4911,634,'_overview','field_5b1023299fc62'),
	(4912,634,'went_well','<ul>\r\n 	<li>You convey warmth and expertise, delivering valuable insight in a confident but down-to-earth manner. You always seemed pleased to be representing BCL Solicitors and we discussed the importance of this: people  including the interviewer  are more likely to listen to what you have to say and believe you, if you appear to be engaged and upbeat about what you are saying.</li>\r\n 	<li>You were right to correct the interviewer in the first interview. Mistakes can often happen in the news factory: as we discussed, broadcast journalists typically do several interviews each day and, while some may be experts on the subject matter at hand, many will not. You did well to correct the interviewer quickly and politely and continue with your purpose in being there: to deliver your prepared messages, correct and continue.</li>\r\n 	<li>You kept the audience in mind and explained technical jargon, such as Deferred Prosecution Agreements, in simple terms  including the relevance of DPAs in tackling white collar crime and contrasting its use between the UK and US. This will make sure your messages get through to as many people as possible.</li>\r\n 	<li>You came across as passionate about what you do. Your pitch, tone, facial expressions and hand gestures drew the audience in to what you were saying, and you maintained excellent eye contact with the interviewer throughout, smiling and even using humour on occasion. You coupled this with interesting human and cultural observations, commenting for example on the use of American methods in the UK: A culture of informantsthats not very British. We particularly liked this. <strong>Myddleton: This was a good answer to a question about the Americanisation of the SFO and whether they were looking to see lessons learnt from across the Atlantic.</strong></li>\r\n 	<li>You used great examples. In particular, your reference to the film Wall Street was an excellent way of illustrating the changes that we might see in the tactics used by the SFO, in a way that the audience could immediately understand, digest and remember  a great skill in the short broadcast format. You did well to position BCL rather decently, stating that you would not approve of the use of informants, as its not very British.</li>\r\n</ul>'),
	(4913,634,'_went_well','field_5b21350c1cb97'),
	(4914,634,'more_work','<ul>\r\n 	<li>Think about your intent and be aware of opportunities to brand BCL Solicitors, especially on radio where, unlike on TV, there are no title cards. Of course, this must be done discreetly and in moderation, otherwise it can come over as crass and cumbersome. For example, in the first interview, when mentioning the Tesco case, you could have mentioned that it was a case your firm worked on.</li>\r\n 	<li>Avoid mentioning your competitors, even in passing. This slipped in towards the end of the first interview when you were talking about recent recruits to the SFO. It wasnt a huge mistake, but it would be better not to give competitors what is effectively free advertising. <strong>Myddleton: We would encourage you never to mention other law firms in any context either positive or negative in a broadcast interview.</strong> <strong>In a background meeting o the market with e.g. Caroline Binham, FT, it is fine but not on the record</strong>. This is your opportunity  you have earned it!</li>\r\n 	<li>Do not rely on the interviewer to tease out the most interesting part of your commentary; take the initiative. For example, we discussed moving the point on supergrasses and the excellent parallel you drew with the film Wall Street to the top of the interview to capture interest from the start, which you did successfully in the second and third interviews.</li>\r\n 	<li>When being filmed, remember to stay put and composed until you are told you can leave  even if the next story comes as a surprise!</li>\r\n 	<li>In the down-the-line interview, you did well to keep still from the waist down (to avoid the appearance of swaying or straying out of shot). But do not be afraid to use your hands  they are a useful outlet for nervous energy and freeing them up will help you to feel more relaxed.</li>\r\n</ul>'),
	(4915,634,'_more_work','field_5b23849124c44'),
	(4916,634,'conclusions','At the beginning of the session, when we asked you about your personal brand and how you wanted to come across, you said:\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li><strong><em>Approachable </em></strong> yes, you achieved this from the start</li>\r\n 	<li><strong><em>Clear </em></strong> yes, you explained technical terms, corrected mistakes and drew easy-to-understand parallels to make your arguments clear and accessible to as wide an audience as possible.</li>\r\n 	<li><strong><em>On it </em></strong><strong></strong> yes, you looked happy to be there and came across as thoughtful and passionate about the issues you were discussing.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nThe key point is to build-in a preparation process in partnership with Myddleton ahead of all media engagements that allows you to identify your key messages and develop memorable proof points so support them. You have the approachability and all-round style to be a powerful media asset for BCL Solicitors.\r\n\r\nKind regards,\r\n\r\nSusan Bookbinder and Shreena Patel'),
