	(4924,635,'overview','It was good to meet you last week. Thank you for your time and effort during the media training session.\r\n\r\nWe hope you found the insight into the journalists agenda useful, and that you will be able to use some of the lessons learned in future engagements.\r\n\r\nIn this note, we capture the main feedback points from the session, where you performed well, and where there are areas to work on.\r\n\r\n<strong><em>Introduction</em></strong>\r\n\r\nIn the session, we focused on the broadcast media and simulated a radio interview on BBC Radio Five Live and two TV interviews: a face-to-face studio interview with Kay Burley on Sky News and a down-the-line clip for a package with the ITV News at Ten. We believe this gives you relevant insight and experience of the different demands of each format so that you can prepare appropriately.'),
	(4925,635,'_overview','field_5b1023299fc62'),
	(4926,635,'went_well','<ul>\r\n 	<li>You were decisive; you did not sit on the fence. This gives the audience confidence in what you say, meaning they are more likely to look to BCL Solicitors for leadership and help in future. For example, in the first interview, instead of accepting the interviewers premise that DPAs are unenforceable, you made your opinion clear: I dont agree with thatI think DPAs are perfectly enforceable and have been enforced historically. <strong>Myddleton</strong>: Good use of examples too e.g. HSBC and other banks understandably risk-averse, anti-money laundering stance.</li>\r\n 	<li>You used the FOAM technique well, combining interesting observations with metaphors. For example, in the second interview you used FOAM to explain why innocent people are being targeted while the guilty are getting away: This is a consequence of two things. One, it is very easy for innocent people to fall through the net of the Proceeds of Crime Act. Secondly, it is a consequence of these agencies going for low-hanging fruit and not having the resources to go after the really serious cases which are much more difficult for them to address. Pithy observations like this will get you asked back by journalists because they know you have interesting opinions to share. And metaphors are a great way of communicating complex ideas quickly and to an almost universal audience, which also means they are very quotable.</li>\r\n 	<li>You used attractive language to add impact. In the second interview you used phrases like draconian and create havoc with innocent peoples lives to impress upon the audience the problems with the current set of rules.</li>\r\n 	<li>You structured your responses to start with the conclusion first  then the evidence. For example, in the second interview, the interviewer started by asking if POCA is a joke. You replied, No, its not a joke; its very serious, then went on to explain why. By avoiding too much detail too early on, this structure makes it easier for the audience to pick up your key messages and means they are more likely to stay tuned in.</li>\r\n 	<li>You used rhetorical techniques like repetition and the rule of three. In your second interview, you said this was only because you werent sure what to say next. That may be so, but remember, writing good prose is very different to writing a good speech (just look at the text of a play versus that of a book). In spoken communication, techniques such as repetition are a very effective way of reinforcing your message.</li>\r\n</ul>'),
	(4927,635,'_went_well','field_5b21350c1cb97'),
	(4928,635,'more_work','<ul>\r\n 	<li>Do not wait for the journalist to prompt you for a headline; take the initiative and front-load the most interesting/valuable part of your commentary. For example, in the second interview your most powerful statement  the one you are most likely to be quoted on  came towards the end when you talked about the bigger cultural issue and the fact that government doesnt fund criminal justice sufficiently because its not a vote-winner. Instead, it would have been great to start the interview with this and use it to frame the conversation. More generally, Myddleton will help you to establish how close to the line you as a firm are happy to go with statements like these.</li>\r\n 	<li>Think about total communication. You had a good level of energy throughout all your interviews, but watch out for tapping and other fidgeting (even on radio) which can betray your discomfort while listening to a tricky question or simply be distracting for the audience.</li>\r\n 	<li>The more your story satisfies the acronym TRUTH, the more likely the journalist is to use it. The H is particularly important and stands for human. In other words, help the audience put themselves in your clients shoes. For example, when talking about having assets frozen or being wrongly accused, paint a vivid picture of what this is like. As we discussed, being forced to take your children out of private school may not elicit the greatest sympathy (in which case just remove the word private), but think about your audience and what matters to them. You started to do this well by the end, for example when you said, Every penny they can spend has to be justified to an outside agency and is scrutinised in detail on a monthly basis and it is a very difficult thing for those families to go through. This positions you as a firm which genuinely cares for and defends its clients.</li>\r\n 	<li>A few on-camera tips. When being filmed, remember to stay put until you are told you can leave. Also keep in mind that the camera saps energy so you must give more to achieve a given level of impact. Finally, in the case of a down-the-line piece, you should try to keep still from the waist down so that you dont appear to sway or stray out of shot. But dont be afraid to use your hands  they are a useful outlet for nervous energy and freeing them up will help you to feel more relaxed.</li>\r\n</ul>'),
	(4929,635,'_more_work','field_5b23849124c44'),
	(4930,635,'conclusions','At the beginning of the session, when we asked you about your personal brand and how you wanted to come across, you said:\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li><strong><em>Insightful </em></strong> yes, especially in the second and third interviews where you made powerful observations and gave the audience an insight into what its like to be accused of such crimes.</li>\r\n 	<li><strong><em>To the point </em></strong> yes, you did this from the start.</li>\r\n 	<li><strong><em>Self-effacing </em></strong> were not sure about this one! But you certainly dont come across as arrogant, and as we have said, your decisive and forthright nature make you an interesting speaker and help to position BCL Solicitors as a leader in its area<strong>. </strong><strong>Myddleton: Broadcast interviews or any media interviews are not the time to want to come across as self-effacing, so we are happy with this! We thought you were very powerful, authoritative and effective,</strong></li>\r\n</ul>\r\nThe key point is to build-in a preparation process in partnership with Myddleton ahead of all media engagements that allows you to identify your key messages and develop memorable proof points so support them. You have the confidence and conviction to be a powerful media asset for BCL Solicitors.\r\n\r\nKind regards,\r\n\r\nSusan Bookbinder and Shreena Patel'),
