	(4938,636,'overview','It was good to meet you last week. Thank you for your time and effort during the media training session.\r\n\r\nWe hope you found the insight into the journalists agenda useful, and that you will be able to use some of the lessons learned in future engagements.\r\n\r\nIn this note, we capture the main feedback points from the session, where you performed well, and where there are areas to work on.\r\n\r\n<strong><em>Introduction</em></strong>\r\n\r\nIn the session, we focused on the broadcast media and simulated a radio interview from the perspective of the business slot on BBC Radio 4s Today programme and two TV interviews: a face-to-face studio interview with Ian King Live on Sky News and a clip for a package with BBC News at Ten. We believe this gives you relevant insight and experience of the different demands of each format so that you can prepare appropriately.'),
	(4939,636,'_overview','field_5b1023299fc62'),
	(4940,636,'went_well','<ul>\r\n 	<li>You articulated your observations well. For example, in the first interview, when asked about how a merger between the SFO and NCA would work out, you responded: Im not sure that it would make any difference; a lot of money would be spent on giving people new business cards and rebranding what will essentially be the same people doing the same jobs. This was excellent: it quickly and clearly highlighted the flaw of a merger as a solution to the SFOs problems. Succinctly expressed observations like this will inspire confidence in BCL Solicitors as a firm of people who think critically and can give clear advice.</li>\r\n 	<li>You used specific examples to illustrate your points. For example, in the second interview, when asked about the lessons to be learned, you cited the SFOs decision not to bring in accounting experts re. Tesco  a case of alleged accounting fraud  as the second time youd seen this happen. The way you presented the facts made the SFOs decision not to bring in accounting experts seem extraordinary  it was also a great way of branding yourself and BCL Solicitors as experts in this area.</li>\r\n 	<li>You made the story human. In the second and third interviews, you talked about the individuals who have to go through the stressful process of defending these proceedings only to find out they should not have been there in the first place. You helped the audience put themselves in your clients shoes by describing details of what it is like to be wrongly accused. We discussed that while it may not be appropriate to share details of a specific case, you can still talk about the types of things your clients are forced to go through. This will also position you as a firm which genuinely cares for and defends its clients.</li>\r\n 	<li>You used metaphors, part of the FOAM technique. For example, not seeing the wood for the trees and I think the issue with informants is making it sufficiently attractive for people to go down that route as opposed to sitting tight and waiting to see if the SFO can get a case of the ground. Metaphors are a great way of communicating complex ideas quickly and to an almost universal audience, which means they are excellent in broadcast situations, where you have limited time to get your points across.</li>\r\n 	<li>You come across as authoritative, composed and thoughtful. Thanks to this and your use of evidence, you managed to criticise the SFO and question its actions without appearing overly aggressive or gratuitous in your criticism. As we discussed, being forthright in your opinions will help you to get headlines, but it is important to know beforehand how far you can go. Myddleton will help you to establish how close to the line you as a firm are happy to go with statements like these.</li>\r\n</ul>'),
	(4941,636,'_went_well','field_5b21350c1cb97'),
	(4942,636,'more_work','<ul>\r\n 	<li>Do not rely on the interviewer to ask you the right question. Instead, look for opportunities to take control of the conversation. For example, use a banal opening question to front-load the most important or interesting bit of what you have to say. You really took this onboard in the second and third interviews, saying straight away that defeat would be a major setback for the SFO  a much more authoritative stance than in the first interview where you started off by saying that the case was ongoing but might be regarded as having some impact on the future of the SFO.</li>\r\n 	<li>Cut out qualifying words, such as quite and perhaps, which dilute the power of your argument, and replace vague descriptors like lots of with vivid imagery. For example, when you say high volumes of data and documentation, do you mean hundreds of files? The more vivid the picture you paint, the more likely the audience will remember it.</li>\r\n 	<li>Try to maintain good eye contact with the interviewer. We discussed the importance of appearing to be pleased to be appearing on behalf of BCL Solicitors: people are more likely to listen to what you have to say and believe you, if you appear to be pleased to be saying it. While your tone, pitch, greeting and posture were all good, you tended to look away quite a lot in the first interview, which could give the impression that you dont want to be there. Even on radio, maintaining good eye contact is important because it will help you to build rapport with the person asking the questions.</li>\r\n 	<li>Be careful not to repeat negative language like Im not saying theyre not up to the job  it is better to use your own, positive language rather than accept that of the interviewer  as you run the risk of being misquoted, especially in the press.</li>\r\n 	<li>Adjust your responses according to the format. You absorbed all our advice and delivered a great sound-bite in the final pre-recorded BBC News interview. Just remember that in this format the reporters questions are not included, so to make sure that your responses can be used in isolation, repeat the part of the question with which you agree. This helps the editing process and increases your chances of being quoted.</li>\r\n</ul>'),
	(4943,636,'_more_work','field_5b23849124c44'),
	(4944,636,'conclusions','At the beginning of the session, when we asked you about your personal brand and how you wanted to come across, you said:\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li><strong><em>Confident </em></strong> yes, you achieved this from the start. Your observations are insightful and delivered with authority. By removing occasional qualifying statements, you will come across as even more confident.</li>\r\n 	<li><strong><em>Friendly </em></strong> yes, you always greeted the interviewer politely with a nod or a quick good morning, and you came across as someone who genuinely cares for his clients.</li>\r\n 	<li><strong><em>At ease  </em></strong>you looked much happier to be speaking on behalf of BCL Solicitors by the last interview, and even greater ease will come with practice!</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nThe key point is to build-in a preparation process in partnership with Myddleton ahead of all media engagements that allows you to identify your key messages and develop memorable proof points so support them. You have the insight and gravitas to be a powerful media asset for BCL Solicitors.\r\n\r\nKind regards,\r\n\r\nSusan Bookbinder and Shreena Patel'),
